## Playbook UI (nitro-web)

- When building UI, **use Playbook first**.
- For React: import from `playbook-ui` (e.g. `import { Button, Card, Flex } from "playbook-ui"`).
- For Rails views: use existing `pb_*` helpers/components instead of custom HTML when possible.
- Prefer matching existing patterns in the codebase over new abstractions.

### AI Metadata (Structured Component Data)

Playbook ships with AI-friendly metadata for validated code generation:

```
node_modules/playbook-ui/dist/ai/
├── index.json               # Component manifest (list of all kits)
├── global-props.schema.json # Props available on ALL components
├── all-schemas.json         # All schemas bundled (bulk lookup)
└── kits/                    # Per-component prop schemas
    ├── button.schema.json
    ├── card.schema.json
    └── ...
```

**When generating UI:**
1. Read `index.json` to find components
2. Read `kits/<name>.schema.json` for valid props/values
3. Read `global-props.schema.json` for universal props (margin, padding, etc.)

### Platform Detection

| File Extension | Platform | Syntax |
|----------------|----------|--------|
| `.tsx`, `.jsx` | React | `<Button variant="primary" />` |
| `.erb` | Rails | `<%= pb_rails("button", props: { variant: "primary" }) %>` |

### Valid Spacing Values

Use tokens, not raw pixels: `none`, `xxs`, `xs`, `sm`, `md`, `lg`, `xl`, `xxl`

```tsx
// Good
<Card padding="md" marginTop="lg" />

// Bad - don't use raw pixels
<Card padding="16px" marginTop="24px" />
```

